{"key":"post-10463864","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10463864</id>\n<content>A good perlite rinse never hurts.&amp;nbsp; When it gets dirty, you can boil it in a large kettle of water, rinse and re-use.&amp;nbsp; It never rots or molds, but it does get dirty when stuff spills into it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It also helps between flushes to rake the perlite with your fingers to fluff it back up.&amp;nbsp; Packed perlite doesn't work well.&amp;nbsp; You want it loose and airy.&amp;nbsp; I like to make little mountains and valleys, because it increases the surface area, thus giving better humidity.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10463876</next>\n<prev>10463856</prev>\n<first>10463805</first>\n<last>10463925</last>\n<when>1244352182</when>\n<utime>06/07/09 08:23 AM</utime>\n</post>"}